snippet.textDisplay:
My two cents here, I'm an Italian (friends and family there) living in Spain (yes, I know, I’m pretty fucked). 
When you say “kids have to go out”, that's absolutely not true. My 7 years old daughter hasn't left home since the 12th of March (it's the 27th when I'm writing this) and she is doing great. Yes, I have a comfortable big house full of games and things she can do but I'm sure your house is bigger than mine. And most of the time they just need you to spend time with them, regardless the size of your house.
There is something you are missing here. When you go out on a bike or surfing, you put you and your daughters in danger: you surely don’t want to go to a hospital in this situation. Apart from your health (and your daughters) you put everyone in jeopardy: you may require first responders to come and get you instead of helping someone else in need and use a hospital bed that someone else should have, because they had to work in contact with people (think about medical personnel, firefighters etc) and got the virus.. So, it’s not just about “If you keep the distance you can go out”! Look for hospital situations in Madrid or Bergamo: a healthcare that is great in a BAU situation, now is just collapsing.
I’m not sure what are the news you get on the virus from the rest of the world (when it started in China information was gray and far away, now it shouldn’t..), but you should be scared by the virus. People in their 30s with no previous pathologies are dying almost on a daily basis and often from nowhere. Many doctors and nurses died too.
Wash your hands, wear a mask but more importantly, if you can, STAY HOME!

snippet.textDisplay:
I own a business called Tony V Studios ( not trying to give myself a shameless plug sorry ) but my client base is 99% of the ones who have been forced to close down. So imagine that you go from looking at record breaking year to zero in a matter of 2 months. One by one clients contacted me telling me that they had to either cancel or postpone their projects indefinitely!
I had no choice but to take whatever job I could get. Now I am working at night at Home Depot stocking shelves so I can make my mortgage and pay my bills. This isn't a poor me comment, its to help everyone reading this realize that you don't have to contract Covid 19 to be drastically impacted by it.
Thanks Casey for sharing what your going through, be safe out there and lets all do what we can to get through this the best we can.
